ite web |url=http://www.timelessvideo.com/dvds/branded2.html |title=Branded: The Complete Second Season |publisher=Timelessvideo.com |accessdate=2014-03-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304045328/http://www.timelessvideo.com/dvds/branded2.html |archivedate=March 4, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On February 16, 2010, Timeless Media Group released ''Branded: The Complete Series,'' a six-disc box set featuring all 48 episodes of the series and several bonus features.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Branded-The-Complete-Series/12850 |title=Branded DVD news: Announcement for Branded - The Complete Series |publisher=TVShowsOnDVD.com |accessdate=2014-03-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317020646/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Branded-The-Complete-Series/12850 |archivedate=March 17, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> More-recent prints cut for syndication are used for the set, and as a result, three minutes are missing from each episode. ''Broken Saber'' (the film re-editing of \"The Mission Parts One, Two, And Three\") is not included.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Branded (TV series)}}\n*{{IMDb title|0058792|Branded}}\n* {{tv.com show|branded|Branded}}\n*{{IMDb title|60191|Broken Sabre}}\n\n{{Larry Cohen}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Branded (TV Series)}}\n[[Category:1960s Western (genre) television series]]\n[[Category:1960s American television series]]\n[[Category:1965 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1966 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by CBS Television Studios]]\n[[Category:Television series by Fremantle (company)]]\n[[Category:Television series by Mark Goodson-Bill Todman Productions]]\n[[Category:Black-and-white American television programs]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Utah]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American television series 1965 - 1966}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = Branded\n| image              = Chuck Connors Anne Morrell Branded 1965.JPG\n| caption            = Connors as Jason McCord and guest star Anna Morrell, 1965\n| show_name_2        =\n| runtime            = 30 minutes \n| genre              = [[Western (genre)|Western]]\n| creator            = [[Larry Cohen]]\n| starring           = [[Chuck Connors]]\n| opentheme          = \"Branded\" by [[Dominic Frontiere]] and Alan Alch\n| composer           = Dominic Frontiere<br />[[Richard Markowitz]] (1.13)\n| executive_producer = Harris Katelman (1965)\n| producer           = Cecil Barker (1965)<br>Andrew J. Fenady\n| company            = The Branded Company (1965)<br>[[Goodson-Todman Productions]]<br>Sentinel Productions\n| distributor = [[King World Productions|King World]]<br>[[CBS Television Distribution]]<br>[[Fremantle (company)|Fremantle]]\n| accessdate         =\n| country            = United States\n| language           = English\n| network            = [[NBC]]\n| picture_format     = [[Black-and-white]]<br>[[Color]]\n| first_aired        = January 24, 1965\n| last_aired         = September 4, 1966\n| num_seasons        = 2\n| num_episodes       = 48\n| list_episodes      =\n| website            =\n}}\n\n'''''Branded''''' is an American [[Western (genre)|Western]] series that aired on [[NBC]] from 1965 through 1966. It was sponsored by [[Procter & Gamble]] in its Sunday night, 8:30&nbsp;p.m. Eastern time period. The series is set in the post Civil War old west. The show starred [[Chuck Connors]] as Jason McCord, a [[United States Army]] [[cavalry]] [[Captain (land)|captain]] who had been [[court-martialed]] and [[Drumming out|drummed out]] of the service following an unjust accusation of [[cowardice]].\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Chuck Connors Branded 1965.JPG|thumb|180px|left|McCord leaving the fort as the gates close behind him]]\nThe opening title credits of each episode in the series feature a depiction of McCord's [[cashiering]] and [[drumming out]] of the military.  He is then sent out of the fort where this ceremony occurred, and the gates are closed behind him. Although the exact date of McCord's cashiering is never given, events and people depicted in episodes place the events of the series itself as sometime during the first administration of President [[Ulysses S. Grant]] (1869-72) and after [[William Seward]] negotiated the [[Alaska purchase]]. The name and location of the fort are also not given; but since [[Bitter Creek (Wyoming)|Bitter Creek]], where the battle that caused McCord's discharge took place, is in southern [[Wyoming]], the location of the fort is presumably within what was in 1869 the [[Wyoming Territory]]. U.S. military forts known to be in operation at that time in the territory included [[Fort Bridger]], [[Fort Fetterman]] and [[Fort Laramie]].\n\nIn the pilot episode, \"The Vindicator,\" McCord is confronted by a newspaper reporter ([[Claude Akins]]) who wants a follow-up story on the Bitter Creek massacre. McCord refuses to cooperate. He knows that General James Reed, McCord's mentor, was on a peace mission to meet representatives of the Cheyenne nation at Bitter Creek. His unit of 31 men was attacked by a group of renegade Indians known as [[Dog Soldiers]]. During the attack, McCord realized that the old general had taken leave of his senses. McCord assumed command, but it was too late. McCord was wounded in the battle and left for dead, the only survivor. He remained in a coma for 10 days after the attack. McCord was later charged with desertion, convicted at court-martial, and cashiered out of the Army.\n\nThe reporter tracks down a widow of the Bitter Creek massacre ([[June Lockhart]]). Her husband was third in command and had written several letters questioning Reed's mental state. Those letters would have been enough to grant McCord a new trial and possibly exonerate him, but McCord convinced the widow to burn the letters to protect Reed's reputation. McCord feared that if Reed's reputation were <!-- subjunctive --> damaged, certain people in Washington, DC, would try to start a new war with the Apaches. McCord chose never to speak about what really happened at Bitter Creek.\n\nMcCord retained the handle of his broken saber with attached [[pommel (sword)|pommel]]. He had the remaining blade sharpened into a long knife, which he used in many episodes. He traveled throughout the [[Old West]], continually confronted by people who refused to believe his innocence, requiring him to prove them wrong.\n\n[[John Pickard (American actor)|John M. Pickard]] appeared in six episodes as General [[Phil Sheridan]]. Other notable guest stars included [[Chris Alcaide]], [[Russ Conway (actor)|Russ Conway]], [[Don Collier]], [[Burgess Meredith]], [[John Carradine]], [[Pat Conway]], [[Alex Cord]], [[Janet De Gore]], [[Dolores del R\u00edo]], [[Chad Everett]], [[I. Stanford Jolley]], [[Martin Landau]], [[June Lockhart]], [[Gregg Palmer]], [[Larry Pennell]], [[Burt Reynolds]], [[Lee Van Cleef]], [[Bruce Dern]], and [[Michael Rennie]].\n\n==Production==\nCreated by [[Larry Cohen]], the show was co-produced for most of its run by [[Goodson-Todman Productions|Mark Goodson-Bill Todman Productions]] in association with Sentinel Productions, Inc. Goodson-Todman was primarily known for game and panel shows such as ''[[What's My Line?]]'', ''[[The Price Is Right (U.S. game show)|The Price Is Right]]'', and ''[[Match Game]]''; those are under [[Fremantle (company)|Fremantle]] now. Present-day U.S. rights to ''Branded'' came into the ownership of [[King World]] before it became [[CBS Television Distribution]]. Many stations that carry ''Branded'' today usually schedule the program alongside others about drifters in the Old West including [[Aaron Spelling]]'s ''[[The Guns of Will Sonnett]]'', which starred [[Walter Brennan]] and [[Dack Rambo]]; as with ''Branded'', King World / CBS also distributed ''Will Sonnett'' in syndication.\n\nParts of the series were filmed at the [[Kanab movie fort]] and Kanab Canyon in [[Utah]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Arc|first1=James V.|title=When Hollywood came to town: a history of moviemaking in Utah|date=2010|publisher=Gibbs Smith|location=Layton, Utah|isbn=9781423605874|edition=1st}}</ref>\n\nThe series followed Connors' series ''[[The Rifleman]]'', but it did not have that show's longevity, lasting only 48 episodes over two seasons. The first season was shot in black and white (with the exception of the three-part story \"The Mission,\" which was shot in color), and the second season of 32 episodes was made in color.\n\nAndrew J. Fenady served as the producer, later executive producer, on the series. Fenady was also the producer of [[The Rebel (TV series)|''The Rebel'']].\n\n==Episode list==\n\n===Season 1 (1965)===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; background:#fff;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#;\"| No.<br />overall\n! style=\"background:#;\"| No. in<br />season \n! style=\"background:#;\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#;\"| Directed by\n! style=\"background:#;\"| Written by\n! style=\"background:#;\"| Original air date\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |EpisodeNumber2=1\n |Title=Survival\n |DirectedBy=[[Richard Whorf]]\n |WrittenBy=[[Larry Cohen]]\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1965|1|24}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |EpisodeNumber2=2\n |Title=The Vindicator\n |DirectedBy=[[Joseph H. Lewis]] \n |WrittenBy=Larry Cohen\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1965|1|31}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=3\n |EpisodeNumber2=3\n |Title=The Test\n |DirectedBy=[[Leonard Horn]]\n |WrittenBy=John Wilder & Jerry Ziegman\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1965|2|7}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=4\n |EpisodeNumber2=4\n |Title=The Rules of the Game\n |DirectedBy=[[Lawrence Dobkin]]\n |WrittenBy=Larry Cohen \n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1965|2|14}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=5\n |EpisodeNumber2=5\n |Title=The Bounty\n |DirectedBy=[[Harry Harris (director)|Harry Harris]]\n |WrittenBy=Larry Cohen\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1965|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=6\n |EpisodeNumber2=6\n |Title=Leap Upon Mountains...\n |DirectedBy=Harry Harris\n |WrittenBy=Andrew J. Fenady\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1965|2|28}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=7\n |EpisodeNumber2=7\n |Title=Coward Step Aside\n |DirectedBy=Harry Harris\n |WrittenBy=''Teleplay by:'' John Wilder & Jerry Ziegman<br />''Story by:'' Larry Cohen \n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1965|3|7}}\n |ShortSummary=Guest star: [[Johnny Crawford]], Connors' co-star from their earlier series, ''[[The Rifleman]].''\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=8\n |EpisodeNumber2=8\n |Title=The Mission*: Part 1\n |DirectedBy=Bernard McEveety\n |WrittenBy=''Teleplay by:'' Jameson Brewer<br>''Story by:'' Larry Cohen \n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1965|3|14}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=9\n |EpisodeNumber2=9\n |Title=The Mission*: Part 2\n |DirectedBy=Bernard McEveety\n |WrittenBy=''Teleplay by:'' Jameson Brewer<br>''Story by:'' Larry Cohen \n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1965|3|21}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=10\n |EpisodeNumber2=10\n |Title=The Mission*: Part 3\n |DirectedBy=[[Allen Reisner]]\n |WrittenBy=Frank Chase \n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1965|3|28}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=11\n |EpisodeNumber2=11\n |Title=The First Kill\n |DirectedBy=Alex March\n |WrittenBy=Frank Chase\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1965|4|4}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=12\n |EpisodeNumber2=12\n |Title=Very Few Heroes\n |DirectedBy=Bernard McEveety\n |WrittenBy=John Wilder & Jerry Ziegman\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1965|4|11}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=13\n |EpisodeNumber2=13\n |Title=One Way Out\n |DirectedBy=Bernard McEveety \n |WrittenBy=Jameson Brewer\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1965|4|18}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=14\n |EpisodeNumber2=14\n |Title=That the Brave Endure\n |DirectedBy=Ron Winston\n |WrittenBy=''Teleplay by:'' Michael Dunn & John Wilder & Jerry Ziegman<br />''Story by:'' Michael Dunn\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1965|4|25}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=15\n |EpisodeNumber2=15\n |Title=Taste of Poison\n |DirectedBy=Ron Winston\n |WrittenBy=''Teleplay by:'' William Putnam & Nicholas Rowe<br />''Story by:'' Larry Cohen\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1965|5|2}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=16\n |EpisodeNumber2=16\n |Title=Price of a Name\n |DirectedBy=Leonard Horn\n |WrittenBy=''Teleplay by:'' Nicholas Rowe<br>''Story by:'' Larry Cohen\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1965|5|23}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=\n}}\n|}\n<small><nowiki>*</nowiki>In color</small>\n\nParts One, Two and Three of the color episode \"The Mission\" were later released as a movie titled ''Broken Sabre,'' with new footage. According to Western Clippings, the re-edited movie version ends with Jason \"regaining his commission and resuming his army career\", thus giving an ending to the series. It also ends with Jason asking a woman to marry him and she says yes. The movie was released to theaters on May 30, 1965.\n\n===Season 2 (1965\u201366)===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; background:#fff;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#;\"| No.<br />overall\n! style=\"background:#;\"| No. in<br />season \n! style=\"background:#;\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#;\"| Directed by\n! style=\"background:#;\"