1.20] [[Kon no Evolution]] ({{lang|ja|\u9b42\u306e\u30a8\u30f4\u30a9\u30ea\u30e5\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3}})\n* [2000.01.19] [[Hero wa Housou Naka]] ({{lang|ja|\u30d2\u30fc\u30ed\u30fc\u306f\u653e\u9001\u4e2d}})\n* [2000.01.21] [[Sennen no Soldier]] ({{lang|ja|\u5343\u5e74\u306e\u30bd\u30eb\u30b8\u30e3\u30fc}})\n* [2001.02.18] [[Hyakujuu Sentai Gaoranger]] ({{Lang|ja|Dynamic Soul!!}})\n* [2002.02.19] [[Ninpu Sentai Hurricaneger]] ({{Lang|ja|Ima Kaze No Naka De}})\n* [2003.02.16] [[Bakuryuu Sentai Abaranger]] ({{Lang|ja|Dino Guts ga Tomaranai}})\n* [2005.02.13] [[Mahou Sentai Magiranger]] ({{Lang|ja|Song For Magitopia}}) (with [[Akira Kushida]] & [[Ichirou Mizuki]])\n* [2003.05.28] [[Sonic drive]]\n* [2005.02.23] [[Ore wa Tokoton Tomaranai!!]] ({{lang|ja|\u4ffa\u306f\u3068\u3053\u3068\u3093\u6b62\u307e\u3089\u306a\u3044!!}})\n* [2005.08.03] [[Cha-La Head-Cha-La|Cha-La Head-Cha-La (2005 Ver.)]]\n* [2006.03.22] [[Choujin Sentai Jetman (song)|Choujin Sentai Jetman (re-issue)]] ({{lang|ja|\u9ce5\u4eba\u6226\u968a\u30b8\u30a7\u30c3\u30c8\u30de\u30f3}})\n* [2006.03.22] [[Hikari Sentai Maskman (song)|Hikari Sentai Maskman (re-issue)]] ({{lang|ja|\u5149\u6226\u968a\u30de\u30b9\u30af\u30de\u30f3}})\n* [2006.03.24] [[Eternal Love 2006]]\n* [2006.11.29] [[Fuuun Musou Ten]] ({{lang|ja|\u98a8\u96f2\u7121\u53cc\u4f1d}})\n* [2008.07.23] [[Super Survivor]]\n* [2008.12.25] [[Hikari no Sasu Mirai e!]] ({{lang|ja|\u5149\u306e\u3055\u3059\u672a\u6765\u3078!}})\n* [2009.11.25] [[Progression (song)|Progression]]\n* [2010.02.10] Ever Last\n* [2010.10.10] [[Battle of omega]]\n* [2011.10.15] [[Kiba -Tusk of Darkness-]]\n* [2013.06.12] Yohsoro ~Hoshi no Umi wo Koete~({{lang|ja|\u30e8\u30fc\u30bd\u30ed\u30fc \u301c\u661f\u306e\u6d77\u3092\u8d8a\u3048\u3066\u301c}})\n\n== See also ==\n* [[UFO Kamen Yakisoban]]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Hironobu Kageyama}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140404161131/http://www.kids-station.com/minisite/anion/ Anipara Ongakukan Official Web Site]\n* [http://www.airblanca.com/ Air Blanca - Hironobu Kageyama's Personal Web Site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061108021352/http://www.solidvox.jp/artist/kageyama.php SOLID VOX Official Web Site]\n* [http://mark2.s28.xrea.com/kageyama/index.html \"Kageyama Complete!\"] A site with a complete chronological discography.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kageyama, Hironobu}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Anime musicians]]\n[[Category:Anime singers]]\n[[Category:Japanese child singers]]\n[[Category:Japanese heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language singers]]\n[[Category:Japanese male rock singers]]\n[[Category:Japanese male pop singers]]\n[[Category:Japanese male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Osaka]]\n[[Category:People from Osaka]]\n[[Category:Tokuma Japan Communications artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Japanese singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n[[Category:Lazy (band) members]]\n[[Category:JAM Project members]]\n", "text_old": "{{No footnotes|BLP=yes|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Hironobu Kageyama\n| image              = KAGEAVATAR.jpg\n| caption            = Kageyama in [[Brasilia]] in 2012.\n| native_name        = \u5f71\u5c71 \u30d2\u30ed\u30ce\u30d6\n| native_name_lang   = ja\n| birth_name        = {{nihongo|\u666f\u5c71 \u6d69\u5ba3|Kageyama Hironobu}}\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1961|2|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Osaka]], Japan\n| death_date         =\n| death_place        =\n| occupation         = {{Flatlist|\n* [[Musician]], [[Singing|singer]]\n}}\n| website            = {{URL|http://airblanca.com}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre              = {{Flatlist|\n* [[J-pop]]\n* [[Music in Japanese animation|Anison]]\n* [[Rock music|rock]]\n* [[hard rock]] \n* [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]\n}}\n| instrument         = {{Flatlist|\n* Vocals, guitar,  harmonica\n}}\n| years_active       = 1977\u2013present\n| label              = {{Flatlist|\n* [[Tokuma Japan Communications]], [[Columbia Music Entertainment]], [[Lantis (company)|Lantis]], First Smile\n}}\n| associated_acts    = {{Flatlist|\n[[Lazy (band)|Lazy]], [[Metal Brothers]], [[JAM Project]]\n}}}}}}\n{{nihongo|'''Hironobu Kageyama'''|\u5f71\u5c71 \u30d2\u30ed\u30ce\u30d6|Kageyama Hironobu|real name written {{lang|ja|\u666f\u5c71 \u6d69\u5ba3}}, born February 18, 1961}} is a Japanese musician and singer prominent in the soundtracks for [[anime]], [[video game]] and [[tokusatsu]] productions. He is sometimes called Kami (Kei) by his fans. Kageyama got his big break at age 16, as lead singer of the rock band [[Lazy (band)|Lazy]]. By the early '80s, the band split and Kageyama went solo. He found major success once he started to sing the theme songs of [[anime]] and [[tokusatsu]] shows. Becoming immensely popular soon after, Kageyama went on to be dubbed the \"Prince of Anime/Tokusatsu Songs\" and is a main fixture for shows to this day. He also got the nickname \"Mr. DBZ\" by fans of ''[[Dragon Ball Z]]'' as he did the most songs for that anime. He is the original member and current leader of the [[Music in Japanese animation|anisong]] band [[JAM Project]]. Also, along with [[Masaaki Endoh]], he hosts ''Anipara Ongakukan'', a TV show aired on the Kids Station Channel that shows live performances of the theme songs of recent anime and tokusatsu shows.\n\nHe is also the voice of Zaruba, a talking ring and sidekick to the titular hero of the [[tokusatsu]] franchise ''[[Garo (TV series)|Garo]]'', for which JAM Project has performed the opening themes.\n\n== Original ==\n* Ky\u014d wo Ikiy\u014d (Solo Debut Song)\n* Suki Suki Suki\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Original albums ===\n* [1981.12.01] [[Broken Heart (Hironobu Kageyama album)|BROKEN HEART]]\n* [1982.04.01] [[It's LIVE 